A proportional relationship can be represented by a line through the origin. If points \((0,0)\) and \((8, 20)\) are on a line, and so is point \((10,z)\), then what is the value of \(z\)?

You can set this up in two different ways...

\[\frac{20}{8}~=~\frac{z}{10}\]

or

\[\frac{10}{8}~=~\frac{z}{20}\]

Either way, you can start by using "cross multiplication".

\[10\cdot 20 = 8z\]

Divide both sides by \(8\).

\[\frac{10\cdot 20}{8} = z\]

Now, I would find common factors in the numerator and denominator. The thorough approach is to find the prime factorization of each number.

\[\frac{\left(2^{1}\cdot5^{1}\right)\cdot \left(2^{2}\cdot5^{1}\right)}{2^{3}} = z\]

Simplify the numerator.

\[\frac{2^{3}\cdot5^{2}}{2^{3}} = z\]

Eliminate common factors.

\[5^{2} = z\]

Evaluate \(z\).

\[z=25\]
